<p>
<seg id=1> At the same time, in the Chinatown area of the Indonesian capital, Jakarta, ethnic Chinese and Indonesian Muslims are working shoulder to shoulder to protect their homes. </seg>
<seg id=2> Since the rioting began in May Chinatown has been the scene of violent conflict. </seg>
<seg id=3> What follows is another report from Voice of America's Ge Lante in Jakarta. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Under the cover of night, the army fired shots to warn rock-throwing youth in Chinatown to disperse. </seg>
<seg id=5> A few hours earlier, a few thousand people had gathered and burned a bank not one kilometer away from the presidential palace. It burned very quickly and spread to neighboring shops. </seg>
<seg id=6> The group of youths used the pole from a street lamp to break open the door of a shop. </seg>
<seg id=7> During the attacks on Chinese on Saturday, a group of people dragged a Chinese person into the street and beat him, and then threw him into a ditch. </seg>
<seg id=8> The army drove an armed troops carrier truck and retrieved the seriously injured person, saving him. </seg>
<seg id=9> Tanks patrolled the streets strewn with rock and broken glass, while troops numbering in the thousands equipped with rifles and tear gas grenades protected the commercial district to keep the rioters from getting close to it. </seg>
<seg id=10> A businessperson with an electronics shop was forced to relocate after the May violence. </seg>
<seg id=11> This reporter saw a 29 year-old youth surnamed Min wearing only short pants with a belt was standing guard behind a roadblock fashioned out of wire netting. </seg>
<seg id=12> The youth, an employee of a computer shop, said that he and his Muslim neighbors were going to be on guard all night to prevent rioters from robbing their houses. </seg>
<seg id=13> Min said that his neighbors made this wire netting after the May violence, but they never thought they would need to use it so soon. </seg>
<seg id=14> In places where there were roadblocks, people carried wooden sticks to drive away strangers. </seg>
<seg id=15> A person named Daxiyate wore a Muslim cap on his head and a Muslim sarong on his body. </seg>
<seg id=16> He told this reporter that more than half of the youthful looters had heard that there had been a disturbance here, and hurried here from areas outside of Chinatown. </seg>
<seg id=17> The rioters looted and destroyed a subway station over a kilometer away. When the army pursued them their shoes and calculators and clothes hangars were left all over the road. </seg>
</p>
